<DOCNO> AP890930-0008 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
house and senate negotiators are telling 
federal arts agencies not to give any money to obscene art but 
theyre backing away from stronger standards proposed by sen jesse 
helms 
under a compromise reached friday the national endowment for 
the arts and national endowment for the humanities would receive 
budgets in the 1990 fiscal year provided they implement new 
standards in giving grants 
the provision is a weakening of a senatepassed measure backed 
by helms rnc that called for banning federal aid for art that 
is obscene or indecent or that denigrates a religion race 
ethnic background age group or handicap 
instead grants would be denied to art that depicts 
sadomasochism homoeroticism the sexual exploitation of children 
or individuals engaged in the sex act 
and borrowing from a supreme court ruling on obscenity the 
conferees said the art works denied funding would have to be 
utterly devoid of significant literary artistic scholarly 
scientific or political value 
the agreement cleared the way for house and senate agreement on 
a bill to provide about 11 billion for federal land and cultural 
programs for the next fiscal year which begins sunday 
the agreement sought to end a controversy over what arts groups 
say is close to censorship helms and his backers said it was a 
matter of whether works considered by many to be obviously 
offensive should be getting taxpayer money 
i dont know if its a victory for anybody said rep sidney 
yates dill the chief house negotiator 
im not fully pleased but its a way of resolving differences 
between the house and senate said sen james mcclure ridaho 
the senate by 6531 voted friday to urge the negotiators to 
adopt the toneddown prohibition on federal assistance 
a day before the senate had rejected helms by a surprisingly 
wide margin voting 6235 against a resolution backing his stand 
helms amendment had been adopted july 26 by voice vote with few 
lawmakers in the chamber 
yates said the compromise probably wouldnt have a significant 
impact on what art gets federal backing 
the endowment hasnt been known to approve very adventurous 
art in the past he said 
the endowments for the arts and humanities would get 250000 in 
the bill to form a commission to study how grants are awarded and 
determine whether criteria are needed for works to qualify for 
grants 
negotiators also agreed that grants this year to the two 
organizations that displayed the art works that sparked the 
controversy will be subjected to congressional review 
senators had sought a fiveyear ban on funding to the 
southeastern center for contemporary art in winstonsalem nc 
and the institute for contemporary art at the university of 
pennsylvania 
the north carolina center exhibited a photograph by andres 
serrano depicting a crucifix in a jar of urine the pennsylvania 
group showed photographs by robert mapplethorpe depicting children 
in erotic poses and homosexual and sadomasochistic themes 
</TEXT>
