<TEXT>
the food and drug administration wants two 
companies to explain their claims that grain used in three new 
breakfast cereal can help lower cholesterol 
the fda said friday that it has serious concerns about the 
amounts of grain general mills and the kellogg co are using in the 
cereals and asked them to submit scientific data showing the levels 
of grain are safe 
general mills makes benefit cereal and kellogg makes heartwise 
and bran buds 
the cereals contain husks of psyllium which contains soluble 
fiber which the companies say is safe and has been shown to help 
reduce cholesterol benefit also contains sugar beet fiber and the 
fda asked general mills to submit data showing it also is safe 
spokesmen for both companies said their cereals are safe and 
that they would submit the requested data 
bran buds has been on the market for a year benefit is being 
sold in selected test markets but heartwise is not on the market 
yet 
proctor amp gamble co which uses psyllium in its metamucil 
laxative raised the question of whether psyllium is a drug or food 
additive the company had asked the fda to pull benefit off the 
market because the cereal had not been subjected to drugtesting 
requirements 
proctor amp gamble had asked the fda to let it make 
cholesterollowering claims for metamucil but was told more study 
was needed we hope the fda will take further action to eliminate 
the inconsistency in allowing these new cereals to make 
cholesterolreduction claims while metamucil cannot company 
spokesman bill dobson said reacting to the fdas action 
the fda outlined its concerns in separate letters to general 
mills and kellogg 
we recognize that recent recommendations concerning diet 
emphasizes the need for consumers to increase their intake of 
fibercontaining foods the fda letters said we generally see 
no problem when this increase is accomplished by the consumption of 
foods high in naturally occurring fiber 
in the case of an ingredient that is intended to be added to 
various food products to increase the levels of fiber in those 
foods however we believe there are some serious concerns that 
should be considered first 
the fda said there are well known safety concerns associated 
with use of psyllium including possible allergic reactions the 
agency noted that geneal mills has warned on its label about this 
possibility provides instructions for its use on the package label 
and advises consuming the cereal with adequate liquids and 
restricting consumption by children 
</TEXT>
