the endangered species designation for the tortoise affects 
desert areas in nevada and utah as well as california 
in nevada where the tortoise is the official state reptile the 
designation is wreaking havoc on the construction boom in las vegas 
the city and several other parties have sued in federal court in 
washington dc claiming restrictions on building should be 
confined only to areas where the respiratory disease is a problem 
delaney said stress caused by noisy and intrusive allterrain 
vehicles also is believed to be taking a toll on the animals and 
vandals have been shooting them in large numbers 
the tortoises also are suffering from poor nutrition because of 
drought conditions that have reduced vegetation and made drinking 
water scarce 
predatory ravens also have been picking off newborn tortoises 
delaney said 
you just wonder if the poor old tortoise isnt on his way out 
and there isnt anything we can do about it he mused 
but he and jim st amant senior cochairman of the nonprofit 
desert tortoise council say the preservation effort is worthwhile 
once theyre gone we dont get a second chance said st 
amant also a biologist with the state department of fish and game 
he noted that the tortoises welfare is considered an indication 
of the quality of the desert habitat and losses of the reptile 
could indicate other species are at risk 
the tortoise population has dropped sharply since the 1970s 
when the density was estimated at about 250 breeding tortoises per 
square mile 
in some areas were down to about 70 per square mile 
delaney said 
the quarantine area is north of mojave a desert city 70 miles 
north of los angeles bordered on the northwest by koehn lake the 
area includes a 28squaremile desert tortoise preserve 
people caught in the area will be cited for trespassing 
officials have said and fines will vary depending on several 
factors 
sheep will be barred from the area in an effort to help increase 
vegetation and preserve the topsoil 
pilot projects also will be tried during the quarantine 
including one irrigation effort possibly involving pipelines run 
from wells on private land 
delaney said he was surprised by the support the tortoise 
preservation effort has garnered even from offroad vehicle groups 
affected by the closure members of one group have volunteered to 
help post quarantine signs he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

