<TEXT>
the historic international 
agreement to allow thousands of east germans in czechoslovakia and 
poland to go west underscores the deep political changes at work in 
the soviet bloc 
in just one eventful night hardline czechoslovakia and 
reformminded poland have taken their places on the widening route 
of east german refugees heading to west germany 
goaded into changes and reforms by soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev the warsaw pact nations are taking a new approach to old 
problems 
in years past east german refugees in warsaw and prague would 
have had little hope of a successful exit an escape from east 
germany often involved a desperate swim a daring leap a frenzied 
dash or a heartstopping flight in a homemade glider across the 
border 
the scene was completely different this weekend west german 
television showed czechoslovak police standing by idly saturday 
afternoon as refugees carried their few belongings in sacks to the 
west german embassy to prepare for the westward journey 
hungary whose communist leadership has called for multiparty 
elections first opened the floodgates on sept 11 by removing 
border fences with austria that action launched an exodus that 
sent nearly 24000 east german refugees to west germany and left 
the hardline communist leadership in east germany furious 
emboldened by hungarys action east german refugees gathered at 
west german embassies in warsaw and prague where their numbers 
swelled to about 4100 they dug in their heels waiting for 
permission to emigrate 
the unusual agreement saturday came after weeks of diplomatic 
